The engraved dwarven runes and murals on this pillar tell not only the history of the duergar people, but point to a major keystone in their culture. Duergar are a coarse, distrustful race, relying only upon themselves and looking askew at others, whether they hail from the Underdark or the surface world. In spite of this, duergar are usually willing to trade with outside races, even those from the surface world, for the sake of prosperity. However, the duergar have absolutely no love for their closest of kin, the shield dwarves. The duergar feel abandoned by them to the onslaught of the mind flayers and have harbored a grudge for millenia.

One mural shows that in -8100 DR, the shield dwarven kingdom of Barakuiir was beset by the mindflayers of Oryndoll who conquered and enslaved the inhabitants. Over the next few millenia of experimentation and manipulation by the mindflayers, the captives from Barakuir eventually became the gray dwarves, now known by their former clan name Duergar. It was around -4000 DR that the duergar rebelled against their slavers in a bloody liberation. With their newfound freedom, the dwarves created many subterranean holdings that have flourished to incredible wealth, influence and power.

No one can mistake drow architecture, even in the absence of the familiar spider motifs of Spider Queen worshippers. The drow aesthetic is given to the beautiful and the spectacular, and House Zau'tar is no exception, magnificent yet alien in comparison to the surrounding unhewn stone. 
L'Obsul's design itself has been influenced by drow city planning; what once would have been overlapping racial enclaves vying for territory are now firmly delineated into districts with clear, artificial borders. Only the stairs appended to some structures and buildings seem tacked on; this is because the elite amongst drow favor clothing that allows them to simply levitate themselves onto balconies, ramparts, and bridges. 

Just like duergar architecture shares similarities with dwarven architecture, drow architecture shares similarities not only with surface architecture, but elven architecture, as well, though seldom would any admit to such. The cords of petrified mushrooms are used for many of the buildings, both because they are easier to work with and decorate but because the texture is softer and more pleasant than stone. 

Faerie fire rather than paint or dye gives color to their buildings. All in all, drow architecture shows that the drow seek to master every aspect of the underdark, even the very structure of the caves themselves.

Here on the very cusp of the Lowerdark, the weight of the world crushes everything: light, sound, the very air itself. Only the strangest and most unnatural creatures of the Lowerdark feel at home here. The rest commit themselves to a long struggle for acclimation, and to date they have done an admirable job: in one direction, the columns of a great duergar keep; in another, a hauntingly beautiful cityscape of drow architecture; in yet another, a towering mushroom forest. 

The pressure in the cavern forces strong notes of brine to wash over the cave from the nearby underport. Shadow and darkness hold dominion in the Lowerdark, and columns of faerie fire wage a terrifying battle, burning with alien vigor to avoid being snuffed out. 

The voice carries but in all the wrong directions, so that a person speaking in front of you can be heard behind you in the same labored breath. The only voice that sounds normal is the voice of the earth itself. If one listens closely, every so often, a low and mournful groan fills L'Obsul with the lungs of a titan, a rumble felt in the walls just as much as it is heard in the air. 

There is no salvation to be found by looking upwards into the great central Shaft. There is only the reminder that you are in a cthonic realm that lurks, that slithers, that hungers.

Value.value: This pale glow is clearly the Faerie Fire spell, an early evocation. Faerie Fire lacks the sting of staring into a normal fire, and so the drow favor it not only for brightening their domains but infusing the atmosphere with rarely perceived colors, especially colors that unsettle or intimidate.
This pale glow has a magical origin in the evocation school. Unlike the harsh light of fire, this light does not irritate the eyes.

This pale glow is clearly the Faerie Fire spell, a simple evocation. Faerie Fire lacks the sting of staring into a normal fire, and so the drow favor it not only for brightening their domains but infusing the atmosphere with rarely perceived colors, especially colors that unsettle or intimidate. Faerie Fire is a common spell to learn amongst drow arcanists, who use it for decorative purposes and for security and hunting purposes. The light of Faerie Fire can be used to outline creatures, obstructing their attempts at obfuscation. Drow of noble blood possess an innate ability to evoke this eerie illumination, giving the children of Lolth all the more reason to revere the ruling caste.

It is an unsavory reality, but the svirfneblin are correct: the best fertilizer for mushrooms and other types of fungus is organic material, especially fecal matter for the nutrients the body declares waste.
What a load of crap. Literally.

It is common policy in L'Obsul to let nothing go to waste. On the urging of the svirfneblin representative, the Council instituted a waste management process that sees many in L'Obsul bringing their waste to the mushroom grove. On the plus side, this has led to much cleaner living spaces and waterways. On the downside, no one wants to live anywhere near the grove on account of the smell. The svirfneblin do not seem to mind, however.

Value.value: Duergar architecture is practical and efficient, but not devoid of purpose. The duergar district is essentially the courtyard of a major clan stronghold poised to defend the Charnag Mine as necessary. The pillars they have constructed are massive and oversized, but only to accomodate the murals and runes they need to express their honor, strength, and prowess.
Judging from the way the duergar built their district, it's a stronghold, and they are ready for war.

The duergar would rarely claim it so, but their architecture still shares many similarities with authentic dwarven architecture. The duergar are far more practical and efficient than the dwarves, however, and as such their designs never fail to communicate their intent. The duergar district is essentially the courtyard of a major clan stronghold poised to defend the Charnag Mine as necessary, and their inner Halls are wide enough and tall enough to accomodate one of the fiercest martial companies in the underdark: a duergar war party. The pillars they have constructed are massive and oversized, but only to accomodate the murals and runes needed to express their honor, strength, prowess, and readiness to survive any collapse of L'Obsul.

value.0:
Deep gnomes have turned their cultivation of mushrooms for food into a wider industry, developing fungi not only for food but creating textiles for durable work clothes and lumber from the fungi's inner cord as well. How the svirfneblin grow such gargantuan mushrooms is a mystery to most, but you have your suspicions. 

A surface kingdom of dwarves discovered and mined a fungus of incredible size filling an expense of the Upperdark between Ched Nasad and Menzoberranzan. These are the only fungi that even come close to approaching its size, and they are but a tiny fraction thereof; but since the titanic toadstools bloom into bioluminescent spores that fill the Shaft on a regular cycle, a process the svirfneblin call a blooming, it stands to reason that the fungus may have spread by a similar method. 

Bioluminescent spores attract a variety of denizens, sentient and otherwise, due to their color. Creatures may take them as food and eat them, only to spread them in dung elsewhere later. The spores' almost faerie-fire like beauty entices sentient creatures who normally do not see much color to take the spore with them where they go. Each is a vector to spread the mushroom's growth. 

L'Obsul is very far from that part of the Underdark, but the deep gnomes have a habit of getting around...

Dogma of Laduguer:  The children of Laduguer have rejected the feckless and feeble gods of their forefathers and withdrawn from their lazy once-kin so as not to be tainted by their weaknesses. Strict obedience to superiors, dedication to one's craft, and endless toil are necessary to achieve wealth, security, and power. Nothing is ever easy, nor should it be. Suffer pain stoically and remain aloof, for to show or even feel emotion is to demonstrate weakness. Those who are weak are undeserving and will suffer an appropriate fate. Adversity is Laduguer's forge, and the harsh trails through which the duergar must pass are his hammer blows - endure all and become stronger than adamantine.

Dogma of Deep Duerra: The children of Laduguer shall conquer the earth and stone from which they sprang and the voids in which they dwell. The seizing of new lands, new wealth and new servitors is the manifest destiny of those who mine the Night Below. Magic is weak, unreliable, and unsubtle when compared to the powers of the mind unless bequeathed and steadied by the will of the gods. By means of the Invisible Art, the duergar shall destroy or enslave all who rely on their petty magics to survive. One day all will bow to the power of the duergar and the brilliance of the Invisible Art.
